{"id":"1804.06916","submitter":"Margaret Beck","authors":"Margaret Beck, Osman Chaudhary, and C. Eugene Wayne","title":"Rigorous justification of Taylor dispersion via center manifolds and\n  hypocoercivity","comments":"37 pages, 0 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s00205-019-01440-2","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Taylor diffusion (or dispersion) refers to a phenomenon discovered\nexperimentally by Taylor in the 1950s where a solute dropped into a pipe with a\nbackground shear flow experiences diffusion at a rate proportional to $1/\\nu$,\nwhich is much faster than what would be produced by the static fluid if its\nviscosity is $0 < \\nu \\ll 1$. This phenomenon is analyzed rigorously using the\nlinear PDE governing the evolution of the solute. It is shown that the solution\ncan be split into two pieces, an approximate solution and a remainder term. The\napproximate solution is governed by an infinite-dimensional system of ODEs that\npossesses a finite-dimensional center manifold, on which the dynamics\ncorrespond to diffusion at a rate proportional to $1/\\nu$. The remainder term\nis shown to decay at a rate that is much faster than the leading order behavior\nof the approximate solution. This is proven using a spectral decomposition in\nFourier space and a hypocoercive estimate to control the intermediate Fourier\nmodes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 18 Apr 2018 21:12:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 7 Nov 2018 19:35:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-09-04"}
